## Project Structure

src/
├── main.c          ← app_main, control task, PWM
├── ble.c / ble.h   ← NimBLE stack, GATT service, characteristics
├── scheduler.c / scheduler.h  ← autonomous schedule task
├── manual.c / manual.h        ← ISR + button board monitor task
└── purifier.h      ← shared types, purifier_status_t, event enums

---

## Build

Requirements:
- PlatformIO
- ESP-IDF framework (installed via PlatformIO)

\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\

sdkconfig. defaults require:

CONFIG_ESP_CONSOLE_USB_SERIAL_JTAG=y
CONFIG_BT_ENABLED=y
CONFIG_BT_NIMBLE_ENABLED=y
CONFIG_BT_CONTROLLER_ENABLED=y
CONFIG_BT_CLASSIC_ENABLED=n
CONFIG_BT_BLUEDROID_ENABLED=n
CONFIG_ESPTOOLPY_FLASHSIZE_16MB=y
CONFIG_ESPTOOLPY_FLASHSIZE="16mb"
CONFIG_BT_NIMBLE_LOG_LEVEL_NONE=y

Build and flash:
```bash
pio run -t upload
pio device monitor

---

## iOS App

The iOS app is a separate Swift/SwiftUI project using CoreBluetooth. 
MVVM architecture fully decouples BLE logic from the UI layer. 
The ViewModel manages device scanning, connection, characteristic discovery, and all read/write/notify operations.

---

## Known Limitations

- Software clock drifts slightly over long periods (no hardware RTC)
- Schedule resets to default on power cut (no NVS persistence by design)
- Logic converter limits expansion to 4 signal channels

